  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the dogmatic over-application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), arguing that treating \"small\" as a substitute for \"cohesive\" leads to extreme fragmentation that hurts productivity, testing, and cognitive load. Using React/Redux as a key example, it illustrates how adding a simple feature can explode into touching many files across technical roles. The tone is analytical with a critical edge, employing recurring metaphors like \"file system shrapnel\" and \"Rube Goldberg architecture\" to frame the problem as organizational debt. The intended audience is software developers—particularly those in web development—who need a pragmatic reminder to focus on meaningful cohesion rather than arbitrary size",
